The five-year accident history:

This facility had one accidental release subject to EPA 40 CFR Part 68, within the last five years. In November 2013 an ammonia truck driver was exposed to anhydrous ammonia while loading his truck.   Approximately 2 pounds of anhydrous ammonia was released during the event.  There were no other on-site or off-site impacts.



The emergency response program:

In accordance with a June 14, 2018 determination by EPA Region 7, the Albany Terminal is designated as a "non-responding" facility, and the information specified in Section 9. Emergency Response of the RMP is based on such designation. Notwithstanding, the Albany Terminal has an extensive emergency response program with a written Emergency Response Plan (ERP). The ERP is designed as a guide to help in determining the magnitude of an incident, the steps needed to bring the incident under control and the requirements to ensure that all federal, state, and local laws are complied with. The ERP is a definitive plan that assigns responsibilities, defines several different methods of communication, designates evacuation procedures, and coordinates with outside assistance. The plan also designates the type and frequency of training that employees are required to have depending on their responsibilities. Furthermore, the plan commits the company's managemen
